  I & I & Z & X & X & Z & I \\
  I & Z & I & Y & I & Y & Z \\
  Z & I & I & Z & Z & I & X
\end{array}~.
\end{align}
It is one of sixteen distinct indecomposable \([[7,1,3]]\) codes \cite{arxiv:0709.1780}.

A seven-qubit \hyperref[topic:quantum-weight-enumerator]{pure} CSS code that corrects a single \(X\) or a single \(Z\) error, but not a single \(Y\) error.
It is the punctured version of the \([[8,3,2]]\) hypercube quantum code and is a phantom code \cite{arxiv:2601.20927}.

A CSS stabilizer tableau for the code is given by \cite[Table 8.6]{arxiv:quant-ph/9705052}\cite[ID 475]{preset:qiskit}
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
  Z & Z & Z & I & I & I & Z \\
  I & Z & I & Z & I & Z & Z \\
  Z & Z & I & I & Z & Z & I \\
  X & X & X & X & X & X & X
\end{array}~.
\end{align}

A \([[7,1,3]]\) code that admits fault-tolerant syndrome extraction using only one ancilla per stabilizer generator measurement.

A stabilizer tableau for the code is given by \cite[ID 108]{preset:qiskit}
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
  X & I & I & I & Z & I & I \\
  I & X & I & I & Z & I & I \\
  I & I & X & I & I & Z & I \\
  I & I & I & X & I & I & Z \\
  I & I & Z & Z & I & Y & Y \\
  Z & Z & Z & I & X & X & Z
\end{array}~.
\end{align}
It is one of sixteen distinct indecomposable \([[7,1,3]]\) codes \cite{arxiv:0709.1780}.

Seven-qubit \hyperref[topic:quantum-weight-enumerator]{pure} QETC that transmutes all single-qubit Pauli errors to logical phase errors.

A stabilizer tableau for the code is given by \cite[Table 1]{arxiv:2310.10278}
\begin{align}
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
  X & X & Y & Y & Z & I & Z \\
  I & Z & X & Y & Y & X & Y \\
  I & I & I & I & I & Z & Z \\
  Z & Z & I & I & Z & I & Z \\
  Z & Z & Z & Z & I & I & I
\end{array}~.
\end{align}
The above stabilizer tableau is equivalent to \cite[ID 646]{preset:qiskit} by applying \(H\) to qubits 1 and 2 and \(SH\) (with \(H\) applied first) to qubits 3 and 4, followed by the qubit relabeling \((1,2,3,4,5,6,7)\to(5,6,1,3,7,2,4)\).

Seven-qubit PI code that realizes gates from the binary icosahedral group transversally.
Can also be interpreted as a spin-\(7/2\) single-spin code.
The codespace projection is a projection onto an irrep of the binary icosahedral group \(2I\).
See Ref. \cite{arxiv:2504.20847} for other non-PI codes realizing \(2I\) gates transversally.

In terms of \hyperref[topic:dicke]{Dicke states}, the unnormalized logical states of one version \cite{arxiv:2305.07023} of this code are
